Reasoning: We need to manipulate the provided Excel file using Python (openpyxl). The instruction describes a VBA task, but we will implement the same logic in Python:

1. Load the workbook from `/sandbox/input/input_spreadsheet/1_341-40_init.xlsx`.
2. Identify the first worksheet (or the one with data).  
3. Insert a new column at position Q (the 17th column). This shifts any existing columns to the right, matching the “new column” requirement.
4. For each data row (starting after the header row), check:
   - Column A (`A`) == `'Government'`
   - Column B (`B`) == `'Germany'`
   - Column C (`C`) == `'Carretera'`
   If all three match, write `'Volkswagen'` into the newly inserted column Q for that row.
5. Save the modified workbook to `/sandbox/output/output_spreadsheet/1_341-40_init.xlsx`.
6. Verify by printing a few rows (header and a couple of data rows) to ensure the new column exists and contains the expected values.

We will perform these steps in a single REPL code block, using openpyxl. After execution we will inspect a short summary to confirm the changes before final submission.
Code:
```repl
import os
from openpyxl import load_workbook, Workbook

# Paths
input_path = "/sandbox/input/input_spreadsheet/1_341-40_init.xlsx"
output_dir = "/sandbox/output/output_spreadsheet"
os.makedirs(output_dir, exist_ok=True)
output_path = os.path.join(output_dir, "1_341-40_init.xlsx")

# Load workbook
wb = load_workbook(filename=input_path)
# Use the active sheet (or first sheet)
ws = wb.active

# Insert a new column at position Q (17th column)
# This will shift existing columns Q.. to the right
ws.insert_cols(17)

# Optional: set header for the new column if a header row exists
header_cell = ws.cell(row=1, column=17)
if header_cell.value is None:
    header_cell.value = "NewColumn"  # generic header; can be changed

# Iterate over rows (skip header)
for row in range(2, ws.max_row + 1):
    val_a = ws.cell(row=row, column=1).value  # Column A
    val_b = ws.cell(row=row, column=2).value  # Column B
    val_c = ws.cell(row=row, column=3).value  # Column C

    # Check conditions (exact string match)
    if val_a == "Government" and val_b == "Germany" and val_c == "Carretera":
        ws.cell(row=row, column=17).value = "Volkswagen"

# Save the modified workbook
wb.save(output_path)

# Verification: print header and first few rows of the new column
print("Header of new column Q:", ws.cell(row=1, column=17).value)
for r in range(2, min(7, ws.max_row + 1)):
    print(f"Row {r} Q={ws.cell(row=r, column=17).value}")
```
